Problem 1¶

1.a.

First start by throwing a signal-free background. For Problem 1 choose a Normal distribution with some modest $\sigma = 2$. Create a million background events.

In [3]:
size = 1000000
bkgd = np.random.normal(0, 2, size)
signal = np.random.uniform(0, 20, size)
data = bkgd + signal

plt.hist(bkgd, bins=100, density=True)
plt.title('Background')
plt.ylabel('Probability Density')
plt.xlabel('Measurement')
plt.show()

plt.hist(signal, bins=100, density=True)
plt.title('Signal')
plt.ylabel('Probability Density')
plt.xlabel('Measurement')
plt.show()

plt.hist(data, bins=100, density=True)
plt.title('Data')
plt.ylabel('Probability Density')
plt.xlabel('Measurement')
plt.show()

In [5]:
signaledges = np.linspace(0,20,40)
dataedges = np.linspace(-7,27,68)

Psd, temp, temp2= np.histogram2d(data,signal, bins=[dataedges,signaledges], density=True)

datacenters = (dataedges[:-1] + dataedges[1:]) / 2
signalcenters = (signaledges[:-1] + signaledges[1:]) / 2
h = plt.pcolormesh(datacenters,signalcenters,Psd.T)
plt.colorbar(h)
plt.title('Observed Data vs True Signal', fontsize=24)
plt.ylabel('True signal, $P(s|d)$', fontsize = 24)
plt.xlabel('Observed data, $P(d|s)$', fontsize = 24)
plt.show()

Problem 2¶

The plots are not centered because having a higher mean in the background means that the observed signal will be shifter higher. This can be seen in the overlayed plots where when the true signal is 15, the observed signal is higher, and when the observed signal is 15, the true signal is lower.
